{"add":{"doc":{"id":"7e8f57f6f08497d1133e8601187c22fc7f337afee478463afb47be5e24ed0b1f","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/ac/Old_Boston_Globe_Building.png/170px-Old_Boston_Globe_Building.png","previous":[],"after":["The Boston Globe was founded in 1872 by six Boston businessmen, including Charles H. Taylor and Eben Jordan, who jointly invested $150,000 (worth $2,952,917 today). The first issue was published on March 4, 1872 and cost four cents. Originally a morning daily, it began Sunday publication in 1877. In 1878, The Boston Globe started an afternoon edition called The Boston Evening Globe, which ceased publication in 1979. In 1964, Tom Winship succeeded his father, Larry Winship, as editor. The younger Winship transformed the Globe from a mediocre local paper into a regional paper of national distinction. He served as editor until 1984, during which time the paper won a dozen Pulitzer Prizes, the first in the paper's history"]}}}